		<item>
		<title>Chair’s Report to the Membership:  November 12th, 2008</title>
		<link>http://www.caw599.ca/?p=664</link>
		<comments>http://www.caw599.ca/?p=664#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 12 Nov 2008 21:10:41 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
		
		<category><![CDATA[Chair's Reports]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.caw599.ca/?p=664</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The Company has agreed to the Union’s request to allow our members that can afford to do so, and that still have room in their RRSP fund, to deposit the entire $2,000 signing bonus directly into your Xstrata Sunlife RRSP account, tax free.
Members will have until Friday, November 14th at 8:00 AM to decide whether [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p id="top" />The Company has agreed to the Union’s request to allow our members that can afford to do so, and that still have room in their RRSP fund, to deposit the entire $2,000 signing bonus directly into your Xstrata Sunlife RRSP account, tax free.</p>
<p>Members will have until Friday, November 14th at 8:00 AM to decide whether they wish to take advantage of this offer. Otherwise, the $2,000 signing bonus will be paid out on Thursday, November 20th. Assignment forms will be available at the gatehouse.</p>
<p>Also take note of the fact that any vacation days that had been pre-approved for the period of our work stoppage that had not already been paid out, will also be paid on November 20th. </p>
<p>Members that were charged with criminal offences during the strike have been suspended for between 1 and 5 days, but they will not be losing their job due to what the Company calls “inappropriate strike line activity”. Your Bargaining Committee will be grieving each and every suspension that has resulted from these alleged offences.</p>
<p>The last time I woke up we were still living in a country where the rule of law counted for something. As far as I know, you are still considered innocent until proven guilty in a court of law. Suspending our members before they have had their day in court is totally inappropriate.</p>
<p>Many of our members are very angry at the Company’s decision to suspend these members for reacting in what they consider to be inappropriate behaviour. </p>
<p>Many of our members consider the fact that the Company has forced us out on strike in 3 out of 4 rounds of bargaining to be inappropriate behaviour.</p>
<p>Many of our members are not happy with the fact that the Company continues to try to divide our membership from its union leadership and consider that to be inappropriate. </p>
<p>I would encourage each and every member to voice their objection to these suspensions to their supervisors. The criminal charges that have been laid against our brothers by the police are unsubstantiated and have been blown way out of proportion. </p>
<p>In the meantime however, I would also encourage each and every member to follow SOP’s with diligence. Given the Company’s actions since October 1st, that would be good advice, as failing to do so could result in more inappropriate Company behaviour.</p>
<p>Ben Lefebvre</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://www.caw599.ca/?feed=rss2&amp;p=664</wfw:commentRss>
